# i18n Standards

## Pattern
Lightweight translation utility that mimics react-i18next API.
Designed to be swapped for the real react-i18next when 
multi-language support is needed (French planned).

## File Location
lib/i18n/
  config.ts          ← getTranslations() function
  locales/
    en/
      hero.json
      navbar.json
      footer.json
      common.json
      about.json      ← add when building About section
      projects.json   ← add when building Projects section
      skills.json     ← add when building Skills section
      journey.json    ← add when building Journey section
      contact.json    ← add when building Contact section

## Usage in Components
```typescript
// In any client component
const { t } = useTranslation('hero');
t('headline_1') // returns "Building AI-native"

// In server components
const t = getTranslations('hero');
t('headline_1') // returns "Building AI-native"
```

## Rules
- Every user-facing string must come from a JSON file
- No hardcoded strings in any component
- Add new JSON file for each new section
- Keys must be snake_case
- Add namespace to Namespace type in config.ts when adding new file
- Always add JSDoc example showing key usage

## Adding a New Section's Translations
1. Create lib/i18n/locales/en/[section].json
2. Add namespace to Namespace type in config.ts
3. Import JSON in config.ts locales object
4. Use useTranslation('[section]') in the component

## Future — Adding French
1. Create lib/i18n/locales/fr/[section].json
2. Add 'fr' to supported locales in config.ts
3. Swap useTranslation hook for react-i18next useTranslation
4. The component code stays identical — only the hook changes